# Stable Quotient of an Ideal

Let `R` be a commutative ring, `I` an ideal of `R`, and `f ‚ąą R`.
The **stable quotient** of `I` with respect to `f`, denoted `I : f^‚ąě`, is the ideal

  `I : f^‚ąě := { g ‚ąą R | ‚ąÉ n ‚Č• 1, f^n * g ‚ąą I }`

In commutative algebra, this is also called the **saturation of `I` with respect to the
multiplicative set `{1, f, f^2, ‚Ä¶}`**. The colon ideals `I : (f^n)` form an increasing chain:

  `I ‚äÜ (I : f) ‚äÜ (I : f^2) ‚äÜ ‚Ä¶ ‚äÜ (I : f^‚ąě)`

and the stable quotient is the union of this ascending chain.

## Main definition

* `Ideal.stableQuotient I f` : the ideal `I : f^‚ąě`.

## Notation

* `I :‚āõ f` : scoped notation for `Ideal.stableQuotient I f`.

## Source

This is definition 67 from the pipeline.

-/

open scoped Classical

variable {R : Type*} [CommRing R]

namespace Ideal

/-- The **stable quotient** `I : f^‚ąě` is the ideal consisting of all `g ‚ąą R` such that
`f^n * g ‚ąą I` for some `n ‚Č• 1`.

Formally: `I :‚āõ f = { g : R | ‚ąÉ n : ‚Ąē, 1 ‚Č§ n ‚ąß f ^ n * g ‚ąą I }`.

This is also written `I : ‚ü®f‚ü©^‚ąě` or `S_f(I)` (saturation with respect to the
multiplicative set generated by `f`) in the literature. -/
def stableQuotient (I : Ideal R) (f : R) : Ideal R where
  carrier := {g : R | ‚ąÉ n : ‚Ąē, 1 ‚Č§ n ‚ąß f ^ n * g ‚ąą I}
  zero_mem' := by
    refine ‚ü®1, by norm_num, ?_‚ü©
    simp
  add_mem' := by
    intro g‚āĀ g‚āā h‚āĀ h‚āā
    rcases h‚āĀ with ‚ü®n‚āĀ, hn‚āĀ, hg‚āĀ‚ü©
    rcases h‚āā with ‚ü®n‚āā, hn‚āā, hg‚āā‚ü©
    let n := max n‚āĀ n‚āā
    have hn_pos : 1 ‚Č§ n := le_trans hn‚āĀ (le_max_left _ _)
    refine ‚ü®n, hn_pos, ?_‚ü©
    rw [mul_add]
    have h‚āĀ' : f ^ n * g‚āĀ ‚ąą I := by
      have hpow : f ^ n = f ^ (n - n‚āĀ) * f ^ n‚āĀ := by
        rw [‚Üź pow_add, add_comm, Nat.add_sub_cancel' (le_max_left _ _)]
      rw [hpow, mul_assoc]
      exact I.mul_mem_left _ hg‚āĀ
    have h‚āā' : f ^ n * g‚āā ‚ąą I := by
      have hpow : f ^ n = f ^ (n - n‚āā) * f ^ n‚āā := by
        rw [‚Üź pow_add, add_comm, Nat.add_sub_cancel' (le_max_right _ _)]
      rw [hpow, mul_assoc]
      exact I.mul_mem_left _ hg‚āā
    exact I.add_mem h‚āĀ' h‚āā'
  smul_mem' := by
    intro r g hg
    rcases hg with ‚ü®n, hn, hg‚ü©
    refine ‚ü®n, hn, ?_‚ü©
    rw [mul_left_comm (f ^ n) r g, smul_eq_mul]
    exact I.mul_mem_right _ hg

/-- Scoped notation `I :‚āõ f` for the stable quotient `I : f^‚ąě`.

The subscript "s" stands for "stable" (as opposed to the single-step colon `(I : f)`). -/
scoped notation:70 I:70 " :‚āõ " f:70 => stableQuotient I f

/-- Membership criterion for the stable quotient. -/
lemma mem_stableQuotient_iff {I : Ideal R} {f g : R} :
    g ‚ąą I :‚āõ f ‚ÜĒ ‚ąÉ n : ‚Ąē, 1 ‚Č§ n ‚ąß f ^ n * g ‚ąą I := by
  rfl

/-- Every element of `I` belongs to `I : f^‚ąě` (take `n = 1`).
So `I ‚äÜ I : f^‚ąě`. -/
lemma subset_stableQuotient (I : Ideal R) (f : R) : I ‚Č§ I :‚āõ f := by
  intro g hg
  refine ‚ü®1, by norm_num, ?_‚ü©
  simpa using I.mul_mem_left f hg

/-- Monotonicity: if `I ‚äÜ J` then `I : f^‚ąě ‚äÜ J : f^‚ąě`. -/
lemma stableQuotient_mono {I J : Ideal R} (hIJ : I ‚Č§ J) (f : R) : I :‚āõ f ‚Č§ J :‚āõ f := by
  intro g hg
  rcases hg with ‚ü®n, hn, hg‚ü©
  refine ‚ü®n, hn, hIJ hg‚ü©

end Ideal

/-! ## Examples -/

section examples

open Ideal

/-- **Example 1**: In any commutative ring, if `g ‚ąą I` then `g ‚ąą I :‚āõ f`. -/
example (R : Type*) [CommRing R] (I : Ideal R) (f g : R) (hg : g ‚ąą I) : g ‚ąą I :‚āõ f :=
  Ideal.subset_stableQuotient I f hg

/-- **Example 2**: Zero is always in the stable quotient (take `n = 1`). -/
example (R : Type*) [CommRing R] (I : Ideal R) (f : R) : (0 : R) ‚ąą I :‚āõ f := by
  rw [Ideal.mem_stableQuotient_iff]
  refine ‚ü®1, by norm_num, ?_‚ü©
  simp

/-- **Example 3**: In ‚Ą§, `(0) :‚āõ 2` consists of all integers `g` such that `2^n * g = 0`
for some `n ‚Č• 1`. Since ‚Ą§ is an integral domain, this forces `g = 0`.

So `(0) :‚āõ 2 = (0)` in ‚Ą§. -/
example : (‚ä• : Ideal ‚Ą§) :‚āõ (2 : ‚Ą§) = (‚ä• : Ideal ‚Ą§) := by
  apply le_antisymm
  ¬∑ intro g hg
    rcases Ideal.mem_stableQuotient_iff.mp hg with ‚ü®n, hn, hg‚ü©
    rw [Ideal.mem_bot] at hg ‚äĘ
    -- hg : 2^n * g = 0, and 2^n ‚Č† 0, so by integral domain property g = 0
    have hp : (2 : ‚Ą§) ^ n ‚Č† 0 := by
      simp
    apply mul_eq_zero.mp at hg
    ¬∑ rcases hg with (h | h)
      ¬∑ exact hp h
      ¬∑ exact h
    ¬∑ -- commutativity
      ring
  ¬∑ -- ‚ä• ‚äÜ ‚ä• :‚āõ 2 is always true
    exact Ideal.subset_stableQuotient ‚ä• (2 : ‚Ą§)

/-- **Example 4**: In ‚Ą§, taking `I = (6)` and `f = 2`, the element `g = 3` is in `(6) :‚āõ 2`
because `2^1 * 3 = 6 ‚ąą (6)`. -/
example : (3 : ‚Ą§) ‚ąą (Ideal.span {(6 : ‚Ą§)}) :‚āõ (2 : ‚Ą§) := by
  rw [Ideal.mem_stableQuotient_iff]
  refine ‚ü®1, by norm_num, ?_‚ü©
  -- 2^1 * 3 = 6 ‚ąą (6)
  simp

/-- **Example 5**: Monotonicity demonstration: if `(2) ‚äÜ (1)` in ‚Ą§ then
`(2) :‚āõ 3 ‚äÜ (1) :‚āõ 3`. -/
example : (Ideal.span {(2 : ‚Ą§)}) :‚āõ (3 : ‚Ą§) ‚Č§ (Ideal.span {(1 : ‚Ą§)}) :‚āõ (3 : ‚Ą§) :=
  Ideal.stableQuotient_mono (Ideal.span_le_span_singleton.mpr (by norm_num)) (3 : ‚Ą§)

end examples
